Airport Market Leakage Code Library and Analysis

Eugene Chong

May 9, 2019

1 Summary and Motivation

Airport market leakage occurs when air passengers choose to travel by car to a more distant hub airport for a flight rather than take a flight to the same destination from a smaller airport closer to their origin. Passengers may be incentivized to leak to a more distant airport for any number of reasons, such as differences in fares, flight frequency, airline brand loyalty, and airport amenities (e.g., parking or retail). Market leakage across a regions airports, such as the seven commercial airports that comprise the Texas-Oklahoma-Louisiana mega-region, is an understudied phenomenon that nevertheless has important implications for regional transportation networks. Passengers who are motivated to leak to distant hub airports represent missed customers for their closer regional airports; these passengers also constitute a significant portion of the roadway users on already heavily trafficked highways connecting a regions airports, negatively impacting congestion and increasing carbon emissions. Developing a model to better understand the relationship between regional airport service imbalances and market leakage can provide a framework by which we can develop policy to limit these negative outcomes.

This document summarizes the code used to clean and analyze the data used for Professor Megan S. Ryerson and Professor Amy M. Kims mega-region airport market leakage study.

The code:

  • Reads in and cleans:
    • Data from the Origin and Destination Survey (DB1B), a 10% random sample of airline tickets published by the Bureau of Transportation Statistics.
    • Data from the Air Carrier Statistics database (T-100), a dataset of domestic non-stop segments reported by US air carriers and published by the Bureau of Transportation Statistics.
    • Shapefiles and network distance data calculated in and exported from ArcMap.
  • Calculates each airports market share for every census tract in a study region using the higher of the airports:
    • Direct flight utility and
    • Connecting flight utility

This code base was adapted from the code that Professors Ryerson and Kim wrote for their paper A drive for better air service: How air service imbalances across neighboring regions integrate air and highway demands (2018). It was updated to:

  • Adopt Tidyverse conventions, which improve readability and performance.
  • Combine the direct and connecting flight utilities, which had previously been considered separately, into a single calculation.
  • Allow users to tweak the coefficients used for the utility calculations by a number of standard errors in any direction.
  • Automate the utility and market share calculations; users can repeat the analysis shown here in other locations by specifying a study region and destination airport, assuming the necessary ArcMap analyses were completed.
  • Automatically generate maps and figures displaying the distribution of airport market shares in a study region.

Future iterations of the code base will:

  • Calculate the network distance between census tract and/or zipcode centroids and study region airports by calling the Google Maps API, removing ArcMap from the workflow.
  • Incorporate functionality to read and analyze DB1B data from different years simultaneously, allowing us examine airport market leakage in a study region longitudinally.
  • Incorporate analysis of ARC ticket purchase data, allowing us to estimate the environmental impact of airport market leakage.

In this vignette, we examine how market shares differ among airports in the Texas-Louisiana-Oklahoma mega-region for flights to Seattle SEA and Atlanta ATL.

1.1 Data Directory

The data currently live in the Box directory for the Airport Market Leakage study. Users can sync the directory to their desktop and access it with the following call, updating it to the directory on their device as necessary.

setwd("C:/Users/eugen/Box Sync/Airport Leakage")

2 Setup

2.1 Load Packages

We call the following packages:

  • tidyverse: Contains the data cleaning (dplyr), functional programming (purrr), and plotting (ggplot2) tools that we use throughout the code.
  • sf: Provides tools to manipulate and plot simple feature objects (i.e., geometries like census tracts).
  • tmap: Includes functionality to create interactive maps. Currently unused.
  • ggrepel: Extends the labeling functionality in ggplot2.
  • gridExtra: Adds functionality to display multiple ggplots side-by-side.
library(tidyverse) 
library(sf)
library(tmap)
library(ggrepel)
library(gridExtra)

2.2 Create a Map Theme

We create a theme to give our maps a consistent appearance.

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(face = "italic"),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(), axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 2)
  )
}

3 Read Data

3.1 Shapefiles

First, we read in the geometries necessary for our analysis: the census tracts and airports for each of our study regions. Currently, we include the Southeast and Texas mega-regions, though for purposes of this vignette we will examine only the Texas region.

The census tracts come in shapefile format already and simply need to be read in. The airports for each region come as coordinates in csv files. We project the coordinates and transform the airports into shapefiles.

# Census tracts for each region
Southeast <- st_read("03.26 Ophelia_GIS + update data/02 piedmont atlantic/GIS/mergedregion/studyarea.shp") %>% 
  rownames_to_column(var = "ID")

Texas <- st_read("03.26 Ophelia_GIS + update data/03 Texas/shapefiles/merged.shp") %>% 
  rownames_to_column(var = "ID")

# Airports for each region
Southeast_airports_shp <- read_csv("Code/Utility and Market Share/Coding Dummy Data/Region 2/Airport Points/airport.csv") %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), crs = 4269, remove = FALSE)

Texas_airports_shp <- read_csv("Code/Utility and Market Share/Coding Dummy Data/Region 1/Airport Points/airport.csv") %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), crs = 4269, remove = FALSE)

3.2 DB1B

Next, we read in the DB1B data. In this vignette, we look at the data for the second quarter of 2015.

datTix2015_2 <- read_csv("Data/DB1BTix/Origin_and_Destination_Survey_DB1BTicket_2015_2.csv", col_names = TRUE)  
datCoup2015_2 <- read_csv("Data/DB1Bcoup/Origin_and_Destination_Survey_DB1BCoupon_2015_2.csv", col_names = TRUE)
datSegment2015 <- read_csv("Data/T_100Seg/Seg_2015.csv", col_names = TRUE)

4 Clean Data

Next, we clean the DB1B data to prepare it for the analysis. We:

  • Narrow the datasets to our variables of interest.
  • Find the total number of flights flown between each Origin and Destination pair.
  • Join the tables together by Itinerary ID and O-D pairing.
  • Remove unnecessary dataframes to reduce processing load.
datCoup2015_2.clean <- datCoup2015_2 %>% 
  select(ItinID, Coupons, Origin, RPCarrier, Passengers, Dest)
rm(datCoup2015_2)

datTix2015_2.clean <- datTix2015_2 %>% 
  select(ItinID, Coupons, Origin, RoundTrip, FarePerMile, RPCarrier, Passengers, ItinFare, MilesFlown)
rm(datTix2015_2)

datSegment2015.clean <- datSegment2015 %>% 
  select(DEPARTURES_SCHEDULED, DEPARTURES_PERFORMED, SEATS, CARRIER, ORIGIN, DEST, AIR_TIME, RAMP_TO_RAMP) %>% 
  mutate(OrgDest = paste(ORIGIN, DEST, sep = "")) %>% 
  group_by(OrgDest) %>%
  summarise(Total_DepScheduled = sum(DEPARTURES_SCHEDULED))
rm(datSegment2015)

# join Tix, Coup, and Segment
db1b_2015.joined <- datTix2015_2.clean %>% 
  left_join(datCoup2015_2.clean, by = "ItinID") %>% 
  rename(Origin = Origin.y) %>% 
  select(-contains(".y"), -Origin.x) %>% 
  rename_at(.vars = vars(ends_with(".x")),
            .funs = funs(sub("[.]x$", "", .))) %>% 
  mutate(OrgDest = paste(Origin, Dest, sep = "")) %>% 
  left_join(datSegment2015.clean, by = "OrgDest") %>% 
  mutate(RoundTrip1 = case_when(RoundTrip == 0 ~ 1,
                                RoundTrip == 1 ~ 2)) %>% 
  select(-RoundTrip) %>% 
  rename(RoundTrip = RoundTrip1) %>% 
  mutate(Connection = ifelse(Coupons / RoundTrip > 1.4, 2, (Coupons / RoundTrip)),
         DestCnx = paste(Dest, Connection, sep = ""))

# remove unnecessary data
rm(datCoup2015_2.clean, datTix2015_2.clean, datSegment2015.clean)

5 Analysis

5.1 Define Regions Airports

We create a vector defining each airport in the study regions. Each of these airports must have a corresponding NEAR csv generated by the ArcMap Network Analyst tool.

TX_airports <- sort(c("DFW", "OKC", "SHV", "AUS", "HOU", "IAH", "DAL", "SAT"))

SE_airports <- sort(c("ATL", "BHM", "CHA", "HSV", "SAV", "TYS"))

5.2 Set Variables of Interest

Here we select our study region and destination airport, as well as a few other parameters for the analysis. Later versions of the code base will include the option to modify the coefficients used in the regressions. We select:

  • study_area: Texas. This points to the Texas region census tracts shapefile we imported earlier.
  • dest: SEA. This is the three-letter code for the destination airport.
  • travel_speed: This is the flight speed we use for calculating the travel time in the connecting flight utility function.
  • dwell_time: This is the dwell time we use in the connecting flight utility function. It is also part of the travel time calculation.
  • file_path: This is the file path where the NEAR csvs generated by the ArcMap Network Analyst tool are located.
  • Coefficients: Here, we specify for each coefficient whether we want to use the base value, the lower bound, or the base value plus/minus any number of standard deviations.
    • Lower Bound: To use the coefficient lower bound, specify 1 for the corresponding *_lower_bound_on object.
    • x Standard Deviations from Base Value: For example, to use a coefficient value that is 2 standard deviations away from the base value, specify 0 for the *_lower_bound_on object and 2 for the *_error_multiplier object.
    • Base value: To use the base value, specify 0 for both the *_lower_bound_on and *_error_multiplier objects.
study_area <- Texas
airport_reg <- TX_airports 
dest <- "SEA" 

travel_speed <- 550 
dwell_time <- 1.5 

file_path <- "C:/Users/eugen/Box Sync/Airport Leakage/Code/Utility and Market Share/Coding Dummy Data/Region 1" 

## direct
# airfare
dir_airfare_lower_bound_on <- 0 # do you want to use the lower bound or not?  1 or 0
dir_airfare_error_multiplier <- 0 # user input - how many standard errors away from base coefficient?  Only applies if "lower_bound_on" is 0.

# frequency
dir_freq_lower_bound_on <- 0 
dir_freq_error_multiplier <- 0

# ground access distance
dir_groundDist_lower_bound_on <- 0
dir_groundDist_error_multiplier <- 0

## connecting
# airfare
cxn_airfare_lower_bound_on <- 0 
cxn_airfare_error_multiplier <- 0

# travel time
cxn_travelTime_lower_bound_on <- 0
cxn_travelTime_error_multiplier <- 0

# ground access time
cxn_groundTime_lower_bound_on <- 0
cxn_groundTime_error_multiplier <- 0

Per Ryerson and Kims paper, we use the following values for the coefficient bases, standard errors, and lower bounds:

This is where we hardcode the values for coefficients, standard errors, and lower bounds that we use in the utility calculations.

## direct
# airfare
dir_airfare_base <- -0.18 # base coefficient
dir_airfare_error <- -0.08 # standard error
dir_airfare_lower_bound <- -0.02
dir_airfare_coefficient <- ifelse(dir_airfare_lower_bound_on == 1, 
                                  dir_airfare_lower_bound, 
                                  dir_airfare_base + dir_airfare_error * dir_airfare_error_multiplier)

# frequency
dir_freq_base <- 0.36
dir_freq_error <- 0.13
dir_freq_lower_bound <- 0.09
dir_freq_coefficient <- ifelse(dir_freq_lower_bound_on == 1,
                               dir_freq_lower_bound,
                               dir_freq_base + dir_freq_error * dir_freq_error_multiplier)

# ground access distance
dir_groundDist_base <- -0.85
dir_groundDist_error <- -0.25
dir_groundDist_lower_bound <- -1.35
dir_groundDist_coefficient <- ifelse(dir_groundDist_lower_bound_on == 1,
                                     dir_groundDist_lower_bound,
                                     dir_groundDist_base + dir_groundDist_error * dir_groundDist_error_multiplier)

## connecting
# airfare
cxn_airfare_base <- -1.1
cxn_airfare_error <- 13 
cxn_airfare_lower_bound <- -0.93
cxn_airfare_coefficient <- ifelse(cxn_airfare_lower_bound_on == 1,
                                  cxn_airfare_lower_bound,
                                  cxn_airfare_base + cxn_airfare_error * cxn_airfare_error_multiplier)

# travel time
cxn_travelTime_base <- -0.047
cxn_travelTime_error <- 2.8 
cxn_travelTime_lower_bound <- -0.01
cxn_travelTime_coefficient <- ifelse(cxn_travelTime_lower_bound_on == 1,
                                     cxn_travelTime_lower_bound,
                                     cxn_travelTime_base + cxn_travelTime_error * cxn_travelTime_error_multiplier)

# ground access time
cxn_groundTime_base <- -1.57
cxn_groundTime_error <- 8.4 
cxn_groundTime_lower_bound <- -1.94
cxn_groundTime_coefficient <- ifelse(cxn_groundTime_lower_bound_on == 1,
                                     cxn_groundTime_lower_bound,
                                     cxn_groundTime_base + cxn_groundTime_error * cxn_groundTime_error_multiplier)

5.3 Clean Study Area Shapefile

We give the study area shapefile an ID that will match the IDs used in the NEAR csvs.

study_area$ID <- as.numeric(study_area$ID)
study_area <- study_area %>% 
  mutate(ID = ID -1) %>% 
  dplyr::select(ID, GEOID, geometry)

5.4 Find Average Fares, Frequencies, and Distances

Next we find the average fares, frequencies, and flight distances for each airport in the study region to the destination airport. For round trip itineraries, we cut the fare and distance in half, assuming that a one-way itinerary would be exactly half the distance and cost.

OriginDest_Fare_Freq <- db1b_2015.joined %>% 
  filter(Origin %in% airport_reg, # flights beginning in our study region
         Dest == dest) %>% # and ending at our destination
  group_by(Origin, RoundTrip, Connection) %>% 
  summarize(Avg_Fare = mean(ItinFare), 
            Avg_Miles = mean(MilesFlown),
            Freq = mean(Total_DepScheduled)) %>% 
  mutate(Avg_Fare = Avg_Fare / RoundTrip, # if round trip, only take half the fare
         Avg_Miles = Avg_Miles / RoundTrip) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(Origin, Connection) %>% 
  summarize(Avg_Fare = mean(Avg_Fare), # now that we have gotten fare and miles per segment, average out the roundtrip column.
            Avg_Miles = mean(Avg_Miles),
            Freq = mean(Freq))

5.5 Prepare NEAR CSVs

We read in the NEAR csvs that were exported from the ArcMap Network Analyst tool. A member of the team previously updated those csvs to include distance in kilometers as well as the calculation for direct flight utility for each airport. We remove those here so that the distance_imports2 object matches the original output from ArcMap.

setwd(file_path)

file_list <- list.files(pattern = "*.csv")

distance_imports <- lapply(file_list, function(x){
  read_csv(x) %>% filter(!is.na(ObjectID))})

# Change the names of the lists to be the name of the corresponding airport in the study region
names(distance_imports) <- str_extract(list.files(file_path, pattern = "*.csv", full.names = FALSE), airport_reg)

# Remove the km conversion and utility function columns.  This is now the export of the Route function, i.e., the output from ArcMap.
distance_imports2 <- lapply(distance_imports, function(x){
  x %>% select(-c(starts_with("KM"), ID, starts_with("UT")))})

5.5 Create New Columns with Distance in KM, Average Fare, Frequency, and Direct and Connecting Utilities

We find the following variables:

  • Average fare of a direct flight to the destination
  • Frequency of direct flights to the destination
  • Ground access distance in kilometers from each census tract to each airport
  • Average fare of a connecting flight to the destination
  • Average total travel time for a connecting flight to the destination
  • Ground access time from each census tract to each airport
  • Utility of taking a direct flight from the airport to the destination
  • Utility of taking a connecting flight from the airport to the destination

We find those variables for each airport (new columns) with respect to each census tract (the rows). We do so using the function map2() from the Tidyverse package purrr. This allows us to run a custom function iteratively over two lists: the distance_imports2 object from the previous step as well as the names of the elements of that object (i.e., the names of the airports in the study region). Using a looping function like map2() allows us to quickly repeat this analysis in study regions that may have different numbers of census tracts or airports. map2() also has the advantage of being significantly faster than using custom for loops. Lastly, we use map2() because it can accept two input lists, as opposed to lapply() (used in the previous code segment), which can only accept one.

distance_imports3 <- map2(distance_imports2, names(distance_imports2), function(y, z) {
  
  # direct variables and utility column names
  Direct_Avg_Fare_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Direct_Avg_Fare_", z, sep = ""))
  Freq_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Freq_", z, sep = ""))
  Ground_access_dist_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Ground_access_dist_KM_", z, sep = ""))
  Direct_UT_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Direct_UT_", z, sep = ""))
  
  # connecting variables and utility column names
  Connecting_Avg_Fare_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Connecting_Avg_Fare_", z, sep = ""))
  Travel_time_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Travel_time_", z, sep = ""))
  Ground_access_time_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Ground_access_time_", z, sep = ""))
  Connecting_UT_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Connecting_UT_", z, sep = ""))
  
  y %>% mutate(ID = IncidentID - 1,
               # Direct variables and Utility
               !!Direct_Avg_Fare_name := ifelse(
                 # ifelse statements: if there is no direct/connecting flight from this origin to the destination, it returns NA.
                 sum(!is.na(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Fare[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                                  OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 1)]) != 0),
                 OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Fare[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                       OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 1)], # select for "no connections"
                 NA), 
               !!Freq_name := ifelse(
                 sum(!is.na(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Freq[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                              OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 1)]) != 0), 
                 OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Freq[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                   OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 1)],
                 NA),
               !!Ground_access_dist_name := Total_Length * 1.609344, # convert to KM
               !!Direct_UT_name := dir_airfare_coefficient * (!!Direct_Avg_Fare_name)/100 + 
                 dir_freq_coefficient * log((!!Freq_name)/365) + 
                 dir_groundDist_coefficient * log((!!Ground_access_dist_name)),
               # Connecting variables and Utility
               !!Connecting_Avg_Fare_name := ifelse(
                 sum(!is.na(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Fare[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                                  OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 2)]) != 0), # select for "yes connections"
                 OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Fare[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                       OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 2)],
                 NA),
               !!Travel_time_name := ifelse(
                 sum(!is.na(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Miles[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                                   OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 2)]) != 0),
                 OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Avg_Miles[which(OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Origin == z &
                                                        OriginDest_Fare_Freq$Connection == 2)] / # take average mileage for flights with cxns
                   travel_speed + # divide that by travel speed
                   dwell_time, # lastly, add dwell time
                 NA),
               !!Ground_access_time_name := Total_Time,
               !!Connecting_UT_name := cxn_airfare_coefficient * (!!Connecting_Avg_Fare_name)/100 +
                 cxn_travelTime_coefficient * (log(!!Travel_time_name)) +
                 cxn_groundTime_coefficient * (log(!!Ground_access_time_name))) %>% 
    dplyr::select(ID, everything(), -c(ObjectID:IncidentID, Total_Length))
})

The output is a list object distance_imports3 that, like the input distance_imports2, contains a certain number of elements, each with the name of an airport in the study region. Those elements are dataframes with the same number of rows each as there are census tracts in the study region. They also contain new columns for each variable weve specified above, but the columns have different names in each list element; they include a suffix that matches the three-letter code for the relevant airport. The structure of distance_imports3 is shown below.

We gave the columns different names in order to facilitate flattening the list below. We use the reduce() function to join the list elements using a series of left_joins(), giving us a single very wide dataframe with one row per census tract and a set of variable columns for each airport.

distance_imports4 <- distance_imports3 %>% purrr::reduce(left_join, by = "ID") %>% # join list dataframes together into one dataframe
  left_join(study_area, by = "ID") # join with shapefile

Then, we keep only the direct and connecting utility columns for each airport and throw out the rest for readability.

distance_imports5 <- distance_imports4 %>% 
  select(ID, GEOID, grep("UT", colnames(distance_imports4), value = TRUE)) # every column is the utility of flying connecting or direct from an airport

We use another looping function to choose, for each airport, the higher value between the direct and connecting flight utilities.

distance_imports6 <- map(airport_reg, function(z) {
  
  # Column names.  These columns will be "choose the higher of the connecting or direct utilities".
  Higher_UT_name <- rlang::sym(paste("Higher_UT_", z, sep = ""))
  
  distance_imports5 %>% mutate(
    !!Higher_UT_name := do.call(pmax, # for each pair of Utility columns containing each respective airport name, choose the higher value 
                                c(distance_imports5 %>% select(contains(paste(z))), 
                                  na.rm = TRUE))) %>% # remove NAs.  If an airport does not have a direct flight to a dest, it would have NAs
    select(ID, GEOID, contains("Higher_UT_")) # give us only ID, GEOID, and the new "Higher Utility" column
  }) %>% 
  purrr::reduce(left_join, by = c("ID", "GEOID")) # unlist and combine into one dataframe
  
distance_imports7 <- distance_imports6 %>% 
  gather(Airport, Utility, grep("UT", colnames(distance_imports6), value = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(ID, GEOID)

5.7 Calculate Market Share

Using the utilities chosen in the previous step, we calculate each airports market share in each census tract for flights to the chosen destination. We then join it back to the study_area object, which contains the spatial information we need to map these market shares.

distance_imports8 <- distance_imports7 %>% 
  group_by(ID, GEOID) %>%
  mutate(Airport = gsub("Higher_UT_", "", Airport), # remove "Higher_UT_" from Airport column
         Total_Mkt = sum(exp(Utility)), # Sum of exponentiated utilities for every airport from each census tract (i.e., the denominator)
         Mkt_Share = exp(Utility) / Total_Mkt) %>% ungroup() # Market share for each airport from each census tract

distance_imports9 <- distance_imports8 %>% 
  left_join(study_area, by = c("ID", "GEOID")) %>% 
  dplyr::select(ID, GEOID, Airport, Mkt_Share, geometry)

5.8 Final Data Outputs

We produce two outputs for our two flavors of map.

  • All Market Shares: Contains a column for each airports market share.
  • Highest Market Share: Includes a column for only the airport with the highest market share.
# every airport has its market share as a separate column
all_Mkt_Shares <- distance_imports9 %>% 
  spread(Airport, Mkt_Share) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

# only the airport with the highest market share is included.
highest_Mkt_Share <- distance_imports9 %>% 
  group_by(ID, GEOID) %>% 
  filter(Mkt_Share == max(Mkt_Share, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(ID, GEOID) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

6.1 Discretize

We create a function for rounding each airports market share to the highest tenth.

discretize <- function(x, Airport) {
  x %>% mutate(fill_breaks = case_when(Airport < 0.1 ~ 0.1,
                                       Airport < 0.2 ~ 0.2,
                                       Airport < 0.3 ~ 0.3,
                                       Airport < 0.4 ~ 0.4,
                                       Airport < 0.5 ~ 0.5,
                                       Airport < 0.6 ~ 0.6,
                                       Airport < 0.7 ~ 0.7,
                                       Airport < 0.8 ~ 0.8,
                                       Airport < 0.9 ~ 0.9,
                                       Airport < 1.0 ~ 1.0))
}
